---
/**
 * Slide 02 · The Quiet Ceiling — foundational skills cap adult mobility.
 * Statement-leaning. Sets up the problem before the evidence (T03) and gap (T04).
 */
---

<section data-slot="02" data-variant="ln-v1" class="deck-section" style="justify-content: center;">
  <span class="deck-kicker">02 / 10</span>

  <div class="max-w-5xl">
    <p class="deck-eyebrow mb-5">The problem</p>
    <h2 class="deck-h2">
      There's a <span class="deck-gradient">quiet ceiling</span> on how far a career can go.
    </h2>
    <p class="deck-lede mt-7" style="max-width: 70ch;">
      It isn't ambition, and it isn't the job market. It's the two skills underneath
      every promotion — <span style="color: var(--color-text); font-weight: 600;">literacy and numeracy.</span>
      Most working adults sit below proficiency in exactly these basics, and the basics
      cap how far the rest of a career can climb.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-2">
    <div class="deck-accent-bar"></div>
    <p class="deck-stat-label" style="max-width: 52ch;">
      A degree can lift the credential without lifting the ceiling — unless the
      foundational skills move too.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
